They should also note that the code deposited in GitHub will be archived via Zenodo to issue a DOI, ensuring it is discoverable and can be cited in associated publications."}, {"elementTitle": "Element 3: Standards:", "selectedErrors": ["None--No errors seen"], "satisfactionScore": "Very Dissatisfied", "additionalComments": ""}, {"elementTitle": "Element 4: Data Preservation, Access, and Associated Timelines", "selectedErrors": ["Other--Please mention in comments", "Clarity--Uses vague language, such as saying data will be shared but not providing details"], "satisfactionScore": "Dissatisfied", "additionalComments": "Element 4.1: The current language is ambiguous. NACDA is a program within ICPSR, so archiving with NACDA already places the data within ICPSR. As written, it is unclear whether the investigator intends to (1) deposit the same dataset in both NACDA and ICPSR, which would result in duplicate DOIs, or (2) deposit aging-related data in NACDA and other types of data in ICPSR. To avoid confusion, the plan should clarify this point. 
Suggested revision:
“De-identified data and associated documentation will be archived with the National Archive of Computerized Data on Aging (NACDA), a domain-specific repository within ICPSR. If additional data outside the scope of NACDA are generated, they may be deposited with ICPSR.”

Element 4.2: The current response states that “all datasets and documentation will be assigned persistent Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs) by the repository.” This is not entirely accurate for ICPSR/NACDA. While ICPSR assigns a persistent study number to every dataset, not all collections automatically receive a DOI. Some datasets do receive DOIs through ICPSR’s partnership with DataCite, but this is not universal. To avoid overstating, the language should reflect that datasets will always have a persistent ICPSR study number, and in many cases may also be assigned a DOI.
Suggested Correction:
“All datasets and documentation will be assigned a persistent ICPSR study number, and many collections are also assigned a DOI through ICPSR’s partnership with DataCite. Metadata records will be indexed in ICPSR/NACDA catalogs and major data discovery portals to facilitate findability.”"}, {"elementTitle": "Element 5: Access, Distribution, or Reuse Considerations", "selectedErrors": ["None--No errors seen"], "satisfactionScore": "Satisfied", "additionalComments": ""}, {"elementTitle": "Element 6: Oversight of Data Management and Sharing:", "selectedErrors": ["Other--Please mention in comments"], "satisfactionScore": "Satisfied", "additionalComments": "This section is strong, but it would be improved by including a contingency plan for potential changes and a description of how DMS activities will be reported in the final progress report.
